A damage assessment team from the Pocatello National Weather Service Forecast Office traveled to Darlington, Idaho on June 22, 2018. The tornado was believed to have touched down around 1:15pm MDT on June 21, 2018, approximately 5 miles northwest of Darlington, Idaho. The assessment team found several large hardwood tree limbs down along Huston Road. The largest diameter limb was 1 foot in diameter. About 1.5 miles down Huston Road from Highway 93, a residence on the south side of the road experienced extensive tree damage as well, including a hardwood tree split near the trunk. A second tree was completely uprooted although the root system appeared to be somewhat shallow, perhaps only a couple of feet deep. A third tree was nearly uprooted. A camper was overturned and a large section of the metal roofing had been peeled back. Some of the trusses off of a garage with a metal roof were ripped off. Video of the tornado showed it traveling to the north of Leslie Butte, although it is not clear if it was still on the ground at this point.
A second video shows the tornado on the ground approximately 1 mile northeast of Darlington around 1:32pm. The video shows the tornado on the ground for at least 3 minutes while east of Darlington. The damage team found a 40 to 50 foot section of barbed wire fencing down along with several metal fencing posts bent over or ripped out of the ground about 1.5 miles east of Darlington. The tornado lifted around 1:38pm MDT. The National Weather Service received reports of wheel lines, a chicken coop, pig pen, a shed destroyed, and a screen door ripped off. However, the damage assessment team was unable to find this damage.
Based on the damage, the final assessment for this tornado is a high-end EF0 with winds of 75 to 85 mph. The tornado is estimated to have been 250 feet wide, 7 miles long, and lasted up to 23 minutes.
A tornado briefly touched down in an open field about 5 miles southwest of Gridley at 3:02PM CDT. The tornado quickly dissipated about one minute later with no damage being observed.

Most of the tornado track was over burnt wheat field and dirt farm fields. No structures or trees were hit. The path length was determined mainly by photos and video submitted to a local television station, since there was no damage path evident. The photos and video showed the tornado was likely moving slower than the parent storm. The tornado formed just east of Highway 153, then tracked east along Route A for several miles. The tornado ended along Route A as it reached the New Madrid County line. State police officers reported the tornado skipped intermittently along the ground.

The tornado began in a cornfield just to the southeast of the intersection of Mendon and Wren-Landeck Roads. Some shingle damage and a few downed large branches were noted at a residence along the path of the tornado as it tracked northwest. The tornado continued into another cornfield before dissipating in a tree line. Damage to a single tree was noted in the front of this tree line at the end of the tornado path. Maximum wind speeds were likely in the 60 to 65 mph range.
A brief tornado was reported along Campbell Road northwest of Clayton. No damage occurred.

The National Weather Service in conjunction with the Walker County Emergency Manager, and with the aid of video provided by the public, determined that a brief EF0 tornado with maximum wind speeds of 80 mph and a maximum path width of 150 yards, travelled 1.3 miles across a portion of eastern Walker County, north of the city of Lafayette. The tornado touched down near the intersection of Wheeler Road and Warren Road, just east of Highway 27, snapping a few trees. The tornado traveled southeast toward Lake Howard Road, producing several areas of damage between Ringgold Road and Lucas Lane, including two small barns that sustained significant damage and several larger trees either uprooted or snapped. A section of roof shingles was pulled up from a two-story home. No injuries were reported.
Trained spotter reported very brief touchdown with no damage.

This brief tornado began at 1021 PM CDT 2 miles northwest of Wheeler, Texas and ended at 1022 PM CDT approximately 1 mile northwest of Wheeler, Texas. The tornado had a path length of about 0.6 miles, and a path width of 50 yards. This tornado was rated EF-0 with an estimated peak wind speed of 80 to 85 mph. EF-0 damage occurred to trees, barns, and 5 homes. One manufactured home was completely destroyed. The other homes had roof damage.

Storm chaser recorded video of non-mesocyclonic tornado near Highwood around 3:55 PM MDT. This tornado lasted about 5-minutes. No damage, injuries, or deaths reported. Location and path of tornado estimated via radar. Width also estimated.
A funnel was observed to briefly touch down in an open field, resulting in minimal damage to crops.
A trained spotter reported a funnel cloud briefly touched down on the outskirts of Calvert City. A few tree limbs were down.

A relatively high-elevation tornado in the Routt National Forest was observed by numerous individuals in Routt County. The rotational winds reached the ground initially near the 8900 foot level. Although the rotational winds were on the ground for no more than a couple of minutes, the associated condensation funnel existed for about 10 minutes. A debris cloud which indicated wind rotation on the ground was observed by some eyewitnesses who photographed the tornado.
A tornado touched down briefly in open country. No damage was observed.
An Ada Police officer observed this tornado near county road 1570 southeast of Ada. This brief tornado did cause some tree damage.
Widely photographed tornado briefly touched down in an open field for less than a minute.
A tornado touched down briefly southeast of Claire City with no damage occurring.
A weak tornado with a maximum wind speed of 60 mph occurred. The tornado was a landspout in nature, and was one of four to occur within a few miles of Fairmont.
A weak tornado with a maximum wind speed of 65 mph occurred. The tornado was a landspout in nature, and was one of four to occur within a few miles of Fairmont.
A weak tornado with a maximum wind speed of 60 mph occurred. The tornado was a landspout in nature, and was one of four to occur within a few miles of Fairmont.
A weak tornado occurred with a maximum wind speed of 65 mph. The tornado was a landspout in nature, and was one of four to occur within a few miles of Fairmont.

This weak tornado skipped along mainly at treetop level near the Moutardier Recreation Area about 1/2 mile south of the Edmonson- Grayson County Line. The tornado snapped the upper reaches of several tree trunks near its initial point near several homes - leaving debris in a circular pattern - then skipped eastward, causing other minor tree damage before dropping down to become a waterspout on Nolin Lake northeast of the Moutardier Marina. The waterspout was captured on video and shared on social media, confirming the existence of the rotation and funnel. The waterspout dissipated as it approached the east shore of the channel.

This tornado touched down in the hamlet of Delphos with tree debris being tossed around. A rather diffuse funnel for much of its existence, very little damage occurred with this tornado. The event was captured on video by a few different storm chasers.

The tornado damage occurred mainly on the north side of Sandy Run Lake, which is about four miles southwest of Norris City. Dozens of trees, some large, were uprooted or broken. The tornado occurred in close proximity to a microburst, which produced equally strong winds. Peak winds were estimated near 85 mph in the tornado.
A brief tornado touched down north of County Road H and east of Quarry Road between Dickeyville and Cuba City. The Grant County Emergency Manager reported no damage with the tornado.
Corn crop damage and large branches down.

On the evening of June 26 a line of storms pushed through the Kansas City Metro area. As these storms exited the metro they produced a tornado that impacted the Lake Lotawana area. The extent of the damage was to trees, as well as to vehicles and lakeside docks and boats. No one was injured by the EF-0 tornado.
An EF0 tornado damaged two sheds, and knocked down corn and branches throughout its path.
Law enforcement information completed the survey of a brief EF0 tornado, which lofted an empty grain bin 200 yards into a nearby pond.
A video showed a brief surface touchdown that kicked up some water in a field, southwest of the intersection of Perry and Miner Roads. This tornado only lasted a few seconds and produced no damage.
Rope tornado moved east towards El Dorado lake. No damage was reported.
Brief small funnel touched down over open country. No damage reported.
Trained spotters confirmed a brief tornado touch down approximately 3 miles south southeast of Manhattan. No damage was reported.
A short path of corn was flattened, and a farm implement was overturned.

The tornado remained over rural areas north of Glen Ullin and impacted no structures. Therefore, the tornado was rated EF0. A wind gust of 66 mph occurred at the Glen Ullin airport west of town. Estimated winds of 75 mph in Glen Ullin resulted in damage to trees in the city. This damage was associated with the Rear Flank Downdraft high wind of the tornado and not the tornado itself.
Delayed report of a tornado touchdown north of town and west of Highway 77.

A weak tornado touched down southeast of Morgantown in the 2800 block of Kingwood Pike. There was roof damage to four structures. One house lost over half its roof, while the others had less than 20 percent of their roofs affected. A support beam to a covered porch was blown out at a residence. Meanwhile a utility pole was ripped loose and landed on the side of a house. There were around 10 trees that were either uprooted or snapped. The estimated maximum wind speed was 65-70 MPH.

The tornado began in a field between the Pennsylvania Turnpike and Brinker Road, where it caused damage to trees and a barn along Brinker Road. A section of the barn's roof was lifted off, as was the roof of a side building. A heavy dairy condenser unit was lifted out of this enclosed building after the roof was removed. Several metal roof panels from this building were lofted and circulated downwind during the tornado's life.
Damage thereafter was spotty and limited to tree debris, but the tornado appeared to resume its intensity after the circulation crossed Armbrust Hecla Road. Residents reported seeing water being lofted from a lake along Cannonball Court as the tornado strengthened, with numerous trees being snapped and uprooted along Cannonball Court/Pheasant Run/Udell Road. A wooden pool fence in this area also was destroyed.
The tornado weakened again as it moved along Udell Road, with very limited tree damage apparent along its path. Based on multiple videos submitted from the Brinkerton Road/Sewickley Creek Road area showing a ground circulation, an aerial survey conducted by the Westmoreland County EMA confirmed additional damage. Damage in this area mainly was in the form of snapped/uprooted trees, and was consistent with an EF-0 rating.

An EF-0 tornado touched down just to the southwest of Arnold Palmer Regional Airport. The most-significant damage in this area was discovered along Henrys Road and Whitfield Road in Unity Township. In this area, light damage to tree limbs was first noted, which escalated considerably along Henrys Road. One property in this vicinity suffered widespread damage to trees, and an open-faced barn lost a large section of its roof. Although much damage to trees was noted, minimal damage to homes from wind was observed.

An EF0 tornado, with a maximum estimated wind speed of 85 mph, touched down across the northern portion of James A. Rhodes Airport near Jackson. It damaged a hanger, including bending some of the metal roof and an overhead door. One single engine aircraft was pushed 30 feet and flipped onto a car, and another was pushed about 60 feet and suffered a landing gear collapse. Several large trees were also snapped. Several videos of the tornado were recorded by bystanders.

A NWS Damage Survey Team surveyed multiple areas across southern Jersey County. The survey team did find one area of concentrated damage just northwest of Elsah which it determined was caused by a brief EF-0 tornado. The tornado touched down about one quarter mile SSW of the Green Acres Road and Elsah Road intersection here 3 pine trees were blown over. The tornado then removed part of the roof from an out building on the west side of Elsah Road. Portions of the roof were found blown across Elsah Road to the southeast. The tornado then crossed Lake Drive just west of Red Bud Court where it twisted a road sign 180 degrees and snapped a number of trees near their base. The tornado continued southeast crossing Elsah Road near Joywood Drive where several trees were again snapped. The tornado dissipated shortly thereafter. The tornado was rated EF0 with max wind speeds of 80 MPH. The path length was 1.40 miles and a max path width of 50 yards. No injuries or deaths were reported with this tornado.

A brief weak tornado occurred, with peak winds estimated near 85 mph. Two garage buildings were blown off their foundations. Numerous trees were uprooted or snapped. Several shingles were blown off a roof. An eyewitness reported watching the tornado destroy the garage buildings and then continue on the ground a few hundred yards.

The tornado was on the ground for 10 miles. No damage was visible from the tornado. However, EF-0 microburst damage was observed to the south of the tornado due to the rear flank downdraft; 2 trees uprooted, barn roof blown off, shed destroyed, and a horse trailer flipped over.
The tornado was on the ground across rural areas for four miles. There were no reports of damage with this tornado.
The tornado briefly touched down and reports indicated there was anti-cyclonic rotation. There were no reports of damage.

Broadcast media reported on moderate roof damage to a 2 story apartment building, where a portion of a roof was removed. Little, if any, surrounding damage was observed. A weak radar rotation was observed in the vicinity at the same time, indicating that the damage was likely caused by a tornado.
A brief touch down of a tornado occurred with maximum wind speeds of 65 mph.
An EF0 with a maximum wind speed of 65 mph occurred.

Doors were blown off a barn, most of the roof panels were blown of a shed and thrown downstream, large tree branches were blown down, and a path of corn in a herringbone pattern occurred from a brief tornado 8 miles south southwest of Friend.

This was a narrow swath of 70-80 mph winds that caused damage to a farmstead and scattered debris up to 2/3rds of a mile to the northeast. Several outbuildings in various stages of decay were damaged. A 2x4 wood piece was driven into the siding of the home. The corn to the south and northeast of the home were untouched at least to visible inspection. A mystery.
This brief, narrow, tornado flattened corn, tore off roof panels of a shed, and collapsed some walls from a small shed.

Based on photographs and videos received from the public, local media, and emergency management, the NWS Melbourne determined a high-end EF-0 tornado, with winds of 80-85 mph, occurred in Tavares. The damage showed a discontinuous tornado track moving to the southwest along a nearly one mile path near U.S. Highway 441. The tornado lasted approximately 5 minutes. The most significant damage occurred to a warehouse/mobile unit located behind a Winn Dixie near the 450th block of East Burleigh Boulevard in Tavares. This structure was destroyed, and a piece of sheet metal was lofted onto a nearby power pole. Also, the Fish Camp Lake Restaurant located at the intersection of U.S. Highway 441 and North Lakeshore Boulevard sustained moderate roof damage. The exterior kitchen exhaust fan was ripped off the roof and thrown onto a nearby street. Adjacent to the restaurant at the Lake Tire & Auto Store, several wood fences were knocked over and a small tree was uprooted, falling onto a trailer. Additional reports of very minor damage occurred along US Highway 441, such as small tree limbs and branches knocked off trees, and small fences knocked over. A member of the public relayed a video from a boat on Lake Eustis showing the tornado as it was impacting the area near the Fish Camp Lake Restaurant.

Several videos from social media show a weak tornado formed along an outflow boundary near Limmer Loop on the east side of Round Rock. From video it appears this was a landspout tornado and not associated with a thunderstorm. There was one backyard shed that was heavily damaged. This damage was near Limmer Loop and Will Smith Dr. The tornado only lasted about a minute or two and appears to have moved southwest toward CR 110 where it quickly dissipated. Maximum winds are estimated to be at 70 mph.

Multiple sources including spotter call and video on social media showed a waterspout that made landfall a few dozen yards south of Juno Beach Pier at 1100AM EDT. The tornado lifted shortly after making landfall.
The Cameron Parish Sheriff's office relayed a report and photo of a waterspout on Black Lake near Hackberry. No damage occurred.

A photo of a waterspout was taken from the Highway 6 bridge over the Toledo Bend Reservoir on the Sabine Parish Louisiana side and posted to Facebook. This waterspout touched down just inside Sabine County Texas, was brief in duration, and did not cause any damage before dissipating.

Multiple photos shared from broadcast media showed a tornado in western Broward County. The tornado occurred west of Griffin Road over the Everglades lasting a few minutes. There was no damage reported as it stayed over the open Everglades.

Reports of this tornado, along with video, were posted to social media. The tornado touched down just off the shore, over Lower Red Lake. It moved on shore roughly two miles west of Ponemah and continued to track to the east-northeast, for another mile or so, before dissipating. Large poplar and ash tree limbs were broken down along this path. Peak winds were estimated at 80 mph.
An NWS employee initially reported the land spout tornado. Later in the evening a local broadcast meteorologist provided video evidence that was given to her from a Pueblo West resident.
A land spout tornado moved south and then turned west before dissipating.

The tornado formed south of Dodge and passed over a recently tilled field, which made it visible 45 miles away. About 35 hay bales were displaced. There was no other damage. The tornado was rated EF0 with estimated wind speeds around 80 mph. This was the second of two tornadoes, minutes apart and from the same parent thunderstorm, in Dunn County this day.

At 3 PM EST, an EF-0 tornado touched down west of Ashford Lake and moved generally east for about one minute. Damage was confined to a narrow area bounded by North Road to the west and Ashford Lake to the east, and by Birchwood drive to the north and Westview Drive to the south. Numerous large trees were uprooted in this area. While the tornado was over the lake, a local resident observed water from the lake was lifted fifty to sixty feet into the air. The tornado then lifted off the surface over the east end of Ashford Lake. Overall, the tornado had maximum winds of 85 MPH. Numerous trees were uprooted by the tornado along its path. Path length was 0.4 miles and width was 225 yards.
A tornado touched down briefly in an open field. Path length and width were estimated.

The local police officer video taped a tornado between Susan Lake, and Fish Lake, west of Ceylon. The tornado was estimated to be 10 yards wide and slowly moved west-northwest. Most of the damage was to a row of trees between the lakes.
Tornado formed in rural Wright County east of Eagle Grove and moved northeast through open crop land.

Tornado develop in rural southern Wright County east of Woolstock and traveled east northeast for the duration of the event. The tornado remained in rural agricultural fields producing only crop damage.
Weak tornado developed in south central Wright county and moved northeast in rural agricultural areas. Tornado was found using high resolution satellite data.

A weak tornado developed just east of Interstate 35 in far eastern Ankeny and moved northeast. Damage was observed to several trees along with other minor damage to fencing and playground equipment as it passed through a small subdivision. The tornado then moved into agricultural land before dissipating.
A weak tornado west of Story City reported via social media. The tornado remained in open agricultural land with only crop damage.
This tornado developed northwest of Blairsburg and moved northeast through agricultural land. The tornado dissipated just prior to crossing County Highway D20. Only damage was to crops.
Tornado remained in agricultural fields northwest of Prairie City for entire path length.
Weak tornado developed just northeast of Roland and moved east northeast in rural agricultural fields. Only damage was to crops. Tornado path was obtained via high resolution satellite imagery.
Tornado developed southeast of Prairie City and tracked to the southeast. Remained in rural areas producing crop and tree damage before dissipating.
Weak tornado north of Collins tracked northeast in rural agricultural fields. Damage only to crops. Tornado path was obtained via high resolution satellite imagery.
Brief tornado east of Otley with little if any damage. Reported by a storm chaser with path found using high resolution satellite imagery.
This was a brief tornado east of Clemons remaining in rural agricultural fields. Damage was limited to corn and soybeans. Path found using high resolution satellite imagery.

This was a satellite tornado which formed on the backside of the parent Pella tornado after it passed into Mahaska county. This tornado was captured on video as it developed and the track is very apparent in high resolutions satellite imagery. It did pass over a farmstead but damage to the structure was unknown. Otherwise, it remained in open agricultural fields.
Tornado developed south of Oskaloosa in rural cropland and did primarily crop damage on its southward path. Path found using high resolution satellite imagery.

A National Weather Service survey found numerous large tree limbs were down, trees uprooted and power lines down. This damage was within a larger area of straight line wind damage. Peak wind speeds were estimated at 80 mph. The tornado path length was 0.12 miles and width maximum was 75 yards. The tornado starting location was 7.5 miles NW of Camdenton and ended 7.4 miles NW Camdenton. The tornado was on the ground for duration of approximately 1 minute.

Drone pictures indicate that a disorganized tornado touched down southwest of the intersection of County Road 6B and Ironwood Road. The NW corner of a barn suffered damage to a cinder block wall. Corn was observed laid down in a semi convergent pattern as the tornado moved northeast across 6B and eventually Ironwood Road where some tree branches were broken along Issac Sells Ditch. The tornado lifted at this point with no further damage noted.

A weak tornado briefly touched down near Highway 21 about one mile east-southeast of Wautoma. Several eyewitnesses observed the tornado on the ground for 10 to 15 seconds. A few white pine trees had branches broken (DI 28, DOD 1).

This very small, skipping tornado did its damage primarily on hilltops between Sparks Ferry Road and the intersection of State Road 135 and Lewellen Road. A few tree limbs and a small fence were downed near Sparks Ferry Road before it moved northeast over a large wooded area and open farmland. The next damage was concentrated about a quarter mile south of Water Tower Road, just west of Highway 135. Here the tornado tore multiple metal roof panels off a barn, blew the southward-facing overhead doors of a garage in, and tore the entrance door off the garage on the west side. The attached home sustained considerable siding and roof damage. A small play structure on the west side of the home was destroyed, with the debris blown to the west-northwest. Debris from the barn and home were scattered in a narrow path through row crops up to a third of a mile to the northeast, where a resident witnessed large sheets of roofing and siding fall into a hay field on the north side of Lewellen Road. A corn field on the south side of Lewellen Road showed cyclonic rotation in a narrow path of flattened corn. The maximum wind speeds with this tornado were estimated at 80 mph.

A tornado touched down north of the intersection of E CR 700 S and S CR 390 E where three trees were uprooted, several tree branches broken and a roof removed from an outbuilding. The tornado continued northeast, crossing S America Road where trees were uprooted and tree limbs broken at a residence where it lifted.

NWS survey, along with eyewitness reports, indicated that a tornado briefly touched down in Miami near the intersection of Southwest 8th Street and Southwest 103rd Avenue. Minor damage to trees, mailboxes, street signs, canopies, and basketball hoops occurred as the tornado moved east-southeast along 900 block of Southwest 101st Avenue and Southwest 100th Court, before the tornado became a waterspout over northwest corner of a large retention pond and lifted.

This short-lived spin-up occurred as a northeast-moving storm interacted with outflow winds from a southeastward-moving storm in eastern Metcalfe County. The first damage occurred along Subtle Road, where a carport was overturned and a large part of a metal outbuilding's roof was torn off, in addition to snapping numerous trees. The tornado then moved east-northeast at tree-top level over wooded areas and farm fields, doing its next major damage a mile away where it pushed a double-wide mobile home to the northwest off its blocks, breaking windows, and ripping off shingles from the roof. The tornado continued on for another mile, causing occasional tree damage, and dropping debris before lifting near the east end of Groce Road, where it peeled roofing material from a metal out building. Maximum wind speeds with this tornado were estimated at 80 to 85 mph.

National Weather Service meteorologists surveyed damage in central Lee County and determined that it was consistent with an EF0 tornado, with maximum sustained winds near 85 mph. The tornado touched down in the city of Opelika near the intersection of South 3rd Street and Avenue D. The tornado tracked south and snapped or uprooted many trees before crossing Interstate 85. It then shifted towards the southeast as it crossed Chewacla Road, where it continued to snap or uproot trees. The tornado shifted back to a southerly track and crossed Highway 69 and Royal Drive. It then took a southwest track before lifting near Stringfellow Road.

A weak tornado occurred on the evening of July 22, 2018 in Heidelberg Township, PA. The well defined path through the corn field and twisted nature of the tree damage and eye witness accounts helped to determine this was tornadic damage. The tornado was brief and moved northwest for around 0.8 miles. Damage started with several small trees and limbs being downed along Church Road near the Heidelberg Church. Further west, areas of corn were blown over, with areas each being blown over in several different directions, near some solar panels at the Heidel Hollow Farm. There was also damage to sheet metal on the sides and roof of a barn at the farm. These areas of damage fell in a relatively straight line.

A waterspout moved onto the beach near the 900 block of North Ocean Blvd. The 15 yard wide funnel proceeded toward the boardwalk for about 100 yards before dissipating and caused no apparent damage to structures. However, beach chairs and umbrellas were tossed into the air. The tornado was rated an EF-0 by a NWS Storm Survey with wind gusts estimated at no more than 65 mph.

A brief EF0 tornado touched down along Rio del Norte along the Intracoastal Waterway in the Palencia area. Minor damage occurred to tow newly constructed roofs and a fence was partially blown down. Several trees were blown down and uprooted in the area.
A tornado touched down in open country. No damage as reported.

The National Weather Service in Baltimore MD/Washington DC confirmed an EF-0 tornado at Thomas Jefferson High School in Lincolnia Virginia.
The tornado touched down briefly just south of the softball field, damaging fences, two sheds, light poles and several trees. A shipping container was lofted over 100 yards as the tornado crossed the softball field moving northeast over an adjacent athletic field. The tornado then lifted over the northeastern part of the school property.
A brief tornado touchdown was reported near A1A and North 19th Street. The tornado moved quickly over water where it became a brief waterspout before dissipating. Damage was not reported.
Two trained spotters photographed a landspout tornado to the north of Casper. The tornado remained over open county and caused no damage.

The Emergency Management Coordinator from Willacy County, Texas, reported a small tornado briefly touched down between Raymondville and San Perlita. There was no structural damage, but patches of sugar cane were blown down based on photo evidence, and a short video confirmed the brief touch down.
A tornado touched down in open country. No damage was observed. A weak tornado moved out of Adams County and into Arapahoe County. It remained in open country and caused no damage.
A tornado touched down in open country. Some minor fence damage was observed.

A EF0 tornado briefly touched down three miles west of Kimball and moved southeast for a few minutes before lifting. A truck driver reported that the funnel he was watching became rain-wrapped before it spun his vehicle 45 degrees.
A tornado touched down briefly in an open field. No damage was observed.
An EF0 tornado briefly touched down just west of US Highway 85 near Gun Barrel. The tornado tracked southeast across the highway and lifted three minutes later in open country.
A brief EF-0 tornado damaged a group of trees, with large tree branches broken.
An EF0 tornado briefly touched down on Kersey Drive north of Cheyenne. The tornado tracked southeast for a few minutes then dissipated.
A tornado touched down briefly but no damage was observed.

Trained spotters reported funnels, debris, and power flashes as the rain wrapped tornado moved southeast. Minimal damage was noted as it moved over open countryside. This tornado moved into Cowley County and dissipated. This tornado moved in from Sumner county and dissipated quickly with no damage.
Weak tornado touched down briefly, less than a minute. In that time, the tornado managed to destroy a garage.
Brief touchdown in open area. No damage.

A waterspout over Kentucky Lake was captured on video by at least one boater. The rope-like funnel took a long, winding path from the cloud base to the water. A small but intense cloud of spray marked the touchdown point. The waterspout moved into Duncan Bay, where it appeared to dissipate near the forested shoreline of the Land Between The Lakes National Recreation Area.

An EF0 tornado touched down in a corn field along Benzler Lust Road just to the east of Benzler Road. The tornado tracked northeast for just over a half mile and lifted as it approached Owens Road. A barn near the initial touchdown lost its roof and a tree was knocked down nearby. Some crop damage also occurred.

Brief tornado caused damage to a total of 3 buildings. Details include partial roof damage, displacement of a roof AC Unit, damage to a business sign, and some small tree damage. Emergency Management officials provided the details for this survey.

NWS storm survey confirmed a weak tornado touched down near the intersection of Highway 201 and Milford Dairy Rd and moved north-northeast for less than two miles before dissipating. Numerous trees were blown down along the path while a couple of outbuildings were heavily damaged.

A EF-0 tornado touched down 2 miles south of the city limits of the City of Charlottesville in the Avon Park area of Albemarle County. The touchdown point at 11:00 AM was near the intersection of Avon Street Extension and Scottsville Road. The tornado tracked northeast, roughly parallel to Scottsville Road. Many trees were uprooted or had large portions snapped off. There was some minor structural damage to Monticello High School involving windows and doors. Also at the school, trees and parking lot lights were downed. A chimney was toppled onto the roof of a home on Galaxie Farm Lane. The tornado dissipated 5 minutes later as it crossed near the intersection of Willow Lake Drive and Scottsville Road.

Information from the Jones County Emergency Manager and local media show that a brief, EF0, tornado with maximum wind speeds of 80 MPH and a maximum path width of 100 yards occurred in the northwest portion of the county on the Piedmont National Wildlife Refuge. The tornado began about a quarter mile south of Round Oak-Juliette Road, traveled northeast parallel to and just south of the road before crossing the road just west of the intersection with Will Russell Road, downing several trees along the path. The tornado continued northeast downing a few more trees and causing minor damage to the metal roof of a home before lifting.

A tornado rated as EF0 on the Enhanced Fujita Scale, with estimated winds up to 85 mph, touched down near Saint Fidelis Catholic Church in College Point, knocking down numerous trees and power lines and peeling siding off houses along a path about 3/4 of a mile long and 100 yards wide. The tornado strengthened as it moved toward Powell's Cove Park, where at least 50 trees where downed in a narrow, convergent pattern highly indicative of a tornado. The tornado briefly moved along the southernmost shoreline of Powell's Cove, and then dissipated over the far eastern end of the park just before reaching 138th Place.

A tornado touched down at 12:24 PM EDT on August 3, 2018 over southwest Greene County in eastern New York and continued 1.9 miles on the ground to the northeast for 8 minutes, ending at 12:32 PM EDT. This weak tornado was approximately 200 feet wide and contained estimated maximum winds of 75 mph. The tornado was rated EF-0. Many trees were snapped and uprooted along the path of this tornado. There was no observed structural damage associated with this tornado.

A NWS storm survey indicated an EF0 Tornado began near Atwater and tracked east for 1.6 miles along Highway 12, and entered Meeker County. Multiple trees and power lines were blown down in the city of Atwater. Some of the trees landed on houses and caused structural damage. This is the continuation of the same EF0 tornado that tracked across Kandiyohi county, and entered Meeker county. This tornado tracked an additional 9.5 miles east along Highway 12, through Grove City, to just northwest of Litchfield. Pockets of tree damage, an overturned trailer, and some other minor structural damage to sheds and pole barns resulted. Straight line wind damage, mostly to trees, was found south of the tornado track and Highway 12. Maximum winds were estimated at 80 mph, with a width of 300 yards.

An EF-0 tornado, with wind speeds estimated at 80 mph, touched down on Redhead Hill Road in northern Woodstock and traveled just over 5 miles on a discontinuous path before lifting up in the Quinebaug portion of Thompson. It was only 8 yards wide. It sliced a single, healthy oak tree in half and flattened small portions of two separate corn fields on Redhead Hill Road in Woodstock. The corn was laid down in differenet directions. A woman saw swirling of trees and other debris as it occurred, despite it being enshrouded in rain. Isolated tree damage also was spotted on Watson Road, near Green Acres Lane, in Quinebaug. The tornado lasted from 936 AM EDT to 945 AM EDT.
Tornado caused a swath of damage to crops, and moved round hay bales. Fences and trees were also damaged along the path.

Drone video revealed that a short duration QLCS tornado touched down across northwestern Buena Vista county. The tornado tracked southeast and was on the ground for less than a minute. Damage was limited to crops and some tree branches.
A video indicated a brief tornado, but not damage reported.
Multiple videos taken around Port Arthur and Groves indicated a landspout briefly occurred near Sabine Lake and Pleasure Island. No damage was noted.

A landspout tornado developed in a shower in the Fish Lake Wildlife Area. The location was approximated by triangulating features from the many photographs of the tornado, talking to the witnesses, and using Google satellite and street view tools. It was not readily possibly to conduct a storm survey to determine its path (it was likely short) and its strength because of the inaccessibility of the area.
Pictures posted to social media indicated a landspout occurred near the town of Lake Arthur. No damage was reported as the landspout remained in a pasture.
A tornado touched down briefly in an open field. No damage was observed.

A landspout tornado produced a narrow swath of damage near Eagle Nest. This is the first documented tornado in the Moreno Valley since at least 1950. The landspout tornado also exhibited anti-cyclonic rotation during its entire lifecycle. It had a classically narrow condensation funnel cloud and formed in a vast open area just west of U.S. 64 between mile markers 283 and 284 near Pepper Sauce Camp. The landspout tornado crossed U.S. 64 very near Elk Lane Rd. tracking slightly north of due east until dissipating over the northeast portion of Eagle Nest Lake. Elevations along the track ranged from approximately 8350 feet to 8175 feet. Approximately 180 feet of barbed wire/picket fence was downed and damaged. Several steel t-posts were sheared or bent nearly 90-degrees. All 10 units that comprise the Pepper Sauce Camp property suffered damage. All but two of sixteen west-facing windows were partially or completely destroyed by flying debris. Windows and storm doors at the main building were partially or completely busted. A small car that was parked and facing east had all but the front windshield busted out. The bed of an old truck used as a marketing sign was lifted and carried about 50 feet toward the southwest. The front windshield of an old Chevrolet C65 truck was struck no less than 75 times by flying debris but remained intact while both side windows were completely busted out. An old hay barn was collapsed and roofing material found 300 feet away. An unoccupied fifth wheel recreational vehicle with an estimated weight of 12,000 pounds was partially lifted, shifted and rolled on its side at the Eagle Nest Campground. Two other RVs sustained damage to include busted windows, including a Class A diesel pusher (dry weight 32,000 pounds) that was oriented nearly perpendicular to the tornado`s path. Damage amounts have been estimated.

A brief EF0 tornado uprooted and snapped trees with many branches down. An industrial building suffered significant roof damage after the garage door was blown in. There was minor roof damage to an additional industrial building. Stainless steel drums and other smaller equipment was damaged from being thrown. Insulation from the damaged roof was deposited along the path of the tornado and into Deerfield Community Park.

A thunderstorm moved across Howard County and produced a landspout four miles northwest of Big Spring. It was located over an open field behind the old Holland Cotton Seed holding facility. No damage was reported by the observer and by the Big Spring EMC who went to the location. The path length and width were estimated.
This information was obtained from social media. The tornado was very small and did not last very long.

A drone survey indicated that numerous crops were pushed down in a convergent path in a field south of County Road 1250 South. A residence on the north side of the road suffered minor shingle damage with a nearby barn losing part of its roof and a tree uprooted in the yard. The tornado quickly lifted after impact the residence. Maximum winds of 60 to 65 mph are estimated.

A tornado touched down in a field about 1.5 miles ESE of Smithfield at 4:38pm CDT. The tornado travelled slowly southeastward, impacting one farmstead along its path. A pole barn and small shed were destroyed, with flying debris from the barn causing minor roof and siding damage to the house. The tornado continued along its path doing minor crop damage along the way before dissipating 3 miles SSW of Cuba at 4:48pm CDT.
Public reports of a landspout tornado northwest of Anza, CA. No injuries or damages were reported.
Six firefighters observed a tornado touch down on the west side of Oxford Junction, Iowa. There was damage to a pipe and a shingles on a structure. The peak estimated winds were 75 MPH.
Very brief touchdown reported by the Fire Chief.
Time lapse video shows a narrow tornado at approximately 30 degrees angle to the ground persisting for several minutes.
No damage was reported with this tornado. According to reports, the tornado occurred near the CR I/CR 11 intersection.
A National Weather Service survey determined that an EF-0 tornado struck a barn resulting in damage to the roof.

A National Weather Service Storm Survey determined that an EF-0 tornado caused damage to tree limbs near Highway NN and Lakehill Road just south of Diggins. The tornado then crossed Highway 60 near Diggins with debris blocking highway and one uprooted tree.
A National Weather Service survey determined that a brief EF-0 tornado touchdown that blew over a center-pivot irrigation system in a field off of West highway V in Verdella.

A National Weather Service storm survey determined an EF-0 tornado touched down over rural NE Newton County, destroying an outbuilding and a grain bin, along with damaging numerous trees. The time was estimated from radar.

A brief EF-0 tornado touched down near the intersection of NE 90th Road and NE 20th Lane. Maximum winds were estimated at 61mph. The tornado width was 25 yards with a path length of 0.10 miles. There were large branches broken.

A National Weather Service storm survey determined that a brief EF-0 tornado touched down near North MO Highway A. The tornado was short-lived lasting nearly 2 minutes before ending near the intersection of North MO Highway A and NE 90th Road. Max winds estimated at 74 mph, width of 25 yards, and a path length of 0.25 miles.
An EF-0 tornado caused damage to soybeans and trees along its half mile path. A trained spotter report and videos were used to determine the time of the tornado. The peak estimated winds were 65 MPH.
This tornado developed along Highway 34 east of Marmaduke. The tornado damaged a few trees and overturned and dragged a semi-trailer designed for carrying grain.
A spotter reported a brief tornado touchdown and a survey of the area found multiple patches of flattened corn in a field along Cougar Road. The stalks were all laying to the northeast.

Retired geologist observed a tornado on his property about 1-mile ESE of Wisdom. 50-lb. deck table was blown about 10 feet, a small greenhouse was leveled, and portions of fences were damaged. His personal weather station recorded a 78-mph peak gust at 16:38 MST. In addition, he estimated the tornado moved eastward at about 25 mph for about 3/4 mile. Thus, it is estimated that the tornado occurred between 16:38 and 16:40 MST.

Damage was noted to flags, a large tree limb and metal casing from a US Bank sign. A small dumpster was also tipped behind the bank. The tornado then tracked to the west northwest through the Wileman Elementary School grounds where numerous large tree limbs were downed. Rubber roofing material on a portion of the school building was lifted and set back in place. The tornado then tracked through residences to the west northwest downing numerous limbs and a rotted/damaged tree. Gutter and roofing damage was noted on one home.

The tornado started on the west side of a ranch and threw a 4-wheeler into a barn. There was additional damage to trees and the roof of a barn at the ranch. The tornado moved across an open field and damaged a calf shed. It then crossed 180th street and 331st avenue and moved through a corn field. Many corn stalks were flattened in a 50 yard wide path before entering an open field and then crossing a hay field destroying a hay bale before dissipating.
Based off spotter photos and high resolution satellite imagery, the tornado tracked for over a half mile through a center pivot farm field around 19 miles north of Highmore.

A storm survey determined that a tornado hit a farm east of Nerstrand. Several trees were downed, and a shed was destroyed. The wind also blew down a power pole, landing on a barn which then caught on fire. The tornado may have started southwest of Nerstrand, but it was impossible to determine from the damage pattern. Maximum winds were estimated at around 70 mph. A storm survey determined that a tornado started just east of Nerstrand MN (in Rice County) and continued into Goodhue County, where is dissipated. It damaged trees and crops.

A tornado touched down just west of a farm, where a definite path was evident in the corn field. It took the tin roof off of much of a turkey barn. An empty grain bin was blown several hundred yards. The southern half of a large machine shed was collapsed. Two windows were blown in at a nearby school, which also had a small portion of its roof torn back. Numerous trees were broken.

Tornado was 1 of 19 tornadoes that occurred across central to east central Wisconsin on the afternoon of August 28th. This tornado went east-southeast of the Village of Marquette and was just west of 73. Widespread straight line winds caused significant tree and crop damage across the county as well.

Tornado was 1 of 19 tornadoes that occurred across central to east central Wisconsin on the afternoon of August 28th. This tornado went through mainly rural areas southeast of Brandon. Widespread straight line winds caused significant tree and crop damage across the county as well.

Tornado was 1 of 19 tornadoes that occurred across central to east central Wisconsin on the afternoon of August 28th. This tornado went through mainly rural areas southwest of Oakfield and crossed Kinwood Rd. Widespread straight line winds caused significant tree and crop damage across the county as well.

Tornado was 1 of 19 tornadoes that occurred across central to east central Wisconsin on the afternoon of August 28th. This tornado went just east of Dundee Mountain and did some brief tree damage along Division Rd. Widespread straight line winds caused significant tree and crop damage across the county as well.

Tornado was 1 of 19 tornadoes that occurred across central to east central Wisconsin on the afternoon of August 28th. This brief tornado went just west of Kohler Andrae State Park. Widespread straight line winds caused significant tree and crop damage across the county as well.
An EF-0 tornado with estimated max winds of 85 mph caused tree and property damage in the village of Baldwin. A few bulidings had collapsed walls, damage to siding, or loss of roofing material.

A tornado with estimated maximum winds of 80 mph touched down south of Alba, and followed a discontinuous path to the northeast, lifting just before the Otsego County line. A number of hardwood and softwood trees were downed.

An EF-0 tornado touched down near the Scott County and Clinton County line. Minor damage to tree branches was observed in this area. The tornado strengthened and caused damage to trees and a house. Towards the end of its path, it caused mainly damage to corn. The peak estimated winds were 80 MPH and the tornado was on the ground for 4.14 miles.

A tornado with estimated maximum winds of 85 mph briefly touched down along the Rifle River, about 4 miles northeast of Sterling. A number of hardwood and softwood trees were knocked over or snapped, damaging a few structures in the process.
A Facebook user posted a video of a landspout tornado near Ute Mountain in Taos County.

An NWS storm survey confirmed that an EF-0 struck near Hickory Corners. Several trees and limbs were snapped on the northwest and northern ends of Little Long Lake in Barry county. Snapped trees also fell on a home.

The tornado mostly had damage indicating 65 mph winds but reached 80 mph at its strongest point halfway through its life. It began at the western Jackson City limits north of the Cascades Golf Course and continued north-northeast to cross Washington Avenue. The tornado then weakened near the railroad tracks near Hibbard Avenue. Many trees or limbs were snapped and several trees were uprooted.

The majority of damage was concentrated in the last 1.5 miles of the path near Cutler Road to the intersection of Hollister and Round Lake Roads. Damage to trees and structures was common along the tornado path.

A weak EF-0 tornado produced mainly tree damage in western Chicago. The first damage was noted on Arthington Street, just west of Cicero Avenue. A continuous path of mostly minor tree damage extended to the east northeast crossing Interstate 290 near Pulaski Road with the final damage noted near Garfield Park, between 5th Avenue and Jackson Blvd near Central Park Avenue. One tree was blown into an apartment building knocking out windows and a couple of large tree limbs fell onto cars.
An EF0 tornado was observed by a storm spotter about 4 miles south southwest of Vinton, Iowa. The tornado briefly touched down with no visible damage.
An EF0 tornado was observed by Emergency Management about 4 miles south southeast of Vinton. The tornado briefly touched down with no visible damage.
Law enforcement observed a brief EF0 tornado touch down with no visible damage.

This brief and weak tornado is estimated to have occurred in a wooded area just west of Poplar Creek between Highway 407 and Pine Bluff Road. A picture of the tornado was relayed by social media and an interview was conducted with the individual who observed the tornado. Time and location were estimated based on radar data. The eyewitness account described a very brief and weak tornado with small pieces of debris and leaves being lofted a few hundred feet off of the surface. Maximum estimated winds were 60 mph.

NWS Storm Survey indicated a weak tornado touched down for a short distance in northern Hancock County. The tornado initially touched down at the intersection of Pinecrest and E Fork Road. At this location, several patches of shingles were ripped off of the east side of a manufactured home and thrown onto the west side of a trailer as well as into surrounding trees. A satellite dish mounted on a pole next to the home was thrown to the ground and a free standing swing was broken. The tornado moved north-northeast to Long Vue Road. It produced minor damage to multiple manufactured homes ranging from a few shingles to small sections of skirting. The most intense damage occurred at a manufactured home near the end of the track. Several large sections of shingles were ripped from the roof and thrown into the nearby field, and skirting was torn in many places. A 10 foot by 12 foot plywood shed was also destroyed.

The tornado touched down on Main Street in Tell City, midway between Steuben and Winkeireid Streets, doing minor damage to one roof and bending an amateur radio antenna tower. Moving east-northeast, the tornado damaged roofs and snapped several large tree limbs, as well as toppling a large but rotting tree that crushed the roof of a garage. A small shed was lofted out of its yard and became entangled in utility lines 30 yards to the northeast. As it crossed Winkeireid Street between 10th and 11th Streets, it buckled in a large overhead door and caused minor damage to the roof of the Indiana Southern Power building. Continuing to the northeast, a large metal carport was lifted and blown 50 feet north into neighboring trees, and more tree limbs were snapped, while a vinyl fence was blown northwest, as was a large trampoline and a patio umbrella, which was entangled in utility lines northwest of its origin.
The tornado continued to cause tree damage as it moved east of 14th street into a more rural area. On Brushy Fork Rd, the tornado snapped the trunks of three large trees, then continued northeast into a wooded area. The last evidence of the tornado was at the north end of Quaker Rd, where small branches were broken.

This weak tornado caused no property damage, however a path of crop damage was visible in drone footage. Peak winds were estimated near 80 mph. The tornado touched down on Highway 279 and continued northeast for about 0.6 miles to Highway 56. The tornado track was based on video and drone footage.

A weak tornado briefly touched down in a soybean field. Peak winds were estimated near 65 mph. The only evidence of the tornado was obtained from video footage. Damage assessment teams from the National Weather Service and the Spencer County Emergency Management Agency found no damage.

This tree-top level tornado did all of its damage 20 to 30 feet above ground. Never more than 50 yards wide, the first evidence of the tornado touching down was one mile south of the water tower on Thomas Lane, where it downed several large branches that blocked the road. Moving northeast over forested land, the next evidence was more tree trunks and branches snapped on Poplar Grove Rd just north of the intersection with Hilldale Rd. The tornado then continued to skip northeast, snapping branches and trunks to the west of Frank Luttrell Rd, before crossing the road and causing minor roof damage to the metal roof of a barn and snapping more tree limbs a third of a mile southeast of North Hancock Elementary School. The tornado dropped small branches and leaves along its path as it continued northeast. The last major tree damage was observed around a home on Adair Rd, where trees were uprooted and trunks snapped in a cyclonic pattern around the home. The only damage to the home, however, was minor roof damage from a branch falling on it. The storm then crossed Adair Rd, lifting somewhere in a wooded area west of a large pond near Beauchamp Lane, where residents witnessed its dissipation.
A brief tornado touched down over rural countryside. No damage was reported.
Public sited a tornado and tree damage was reported off Winston Farm Road off of Route 45.

A tornado touched down near Deep Run in association with hurricane Florence. The damage path started along Big Oak Road where up to 5 homes sustained roof damage. Most of this damage occurred in the direction of the storm motion but some shingle loss was in the opposite direction. Minor tree damage was also observed. The damage path continued northwest to Deep Run where minor damage was found near highway 11 and along Old North Carolina 11. This included minor shingle damage, some uprooted or snapped trees. The damage path ended along highway 903 near but mainly north of Liddell Road where more trees were snapped along with minor shingle loss to some homes. The damage was sporadic and consistent with winds in the 75 to 85 mph range due to the loss of shingles and some uprooted trees. The time was estimated based on radar data.

A tornado touched down near Pleasant Hill in association with hurricane Florence. The damage path started along Vine Swamps Road over the extreme western part of Jones County. The beginning time and location was adjusted based on radar due to the inability to access areas east of here. Damage consisted of softwood trees uprooted in the opposite direction of storm motion along with some minor shingle damage. More damage was found just west of highway 258 near Zack Howard Road where a large tree was uprooted and again in the opposite direction of the storm motion. Most of the damage was quite sporadic on the path and was not as concentrated as other storms surveyed thus far. Therefore the wind speed was estimated to be between 75 and 85 mph, mainly due to the uprooted softwood trees and minor shingle loss. The time was estimated based on radar data.

Tornado damage was observed in a half mile path starting in the woods southeast of Great Oak Drive in the Deerfield community in Hampstead NC. The EF-0 tornado moved across Great Oak Drive to East Creek View Drive before it lifted over a tidal creek located northwest of East Creek View Drive. The tornado mainly snapped trees as it moved quickly toward the northwest. It flipped a boat onto a car along East Creek View Drive and damaged a detached garage. Before the tornado lifted it flipped a boat dock on the tidal creek.

A brief tornado touched down on the north side of Porters Neck Road between Porters Neck Road and Tibbys Drive. The tornado moved NW for less than 2 minutes and snapped a couple dozen trees up to 16 in diameter and uprooted a few large trees.

A brief tornado touched down on the south side of Biscayne Drive at Pages Creek. The tornado moved NW for about 2 minutes and snapped a couple dozen trees up to 14 in diameter, uprooted several large trees, and caused significant roof damage to a home on Biscayne Drive. The tornado lifted near the intersection of Bayshore Drive and Biscayne Drive. It touched down again briefly on the west side of Market Street (US-17) near the intersection of Yvonne Road and Jacqueline Drive. In a wooded area near the Cedarbrook Arabians horse training facility, several pine trees up to 14 in diameter were snapped or uprooted on both sides of Yvonne Drive.

A tornado touched down briefly along Blue Clay Road north of I-140 and west of North College Road. Several hardwood trees up to ten inches in diameter were snapped off approximately 15 feet off the ground.
An EF-0 tornado, with winds estimated at 75 mph touched down along Split Rail Dr. Several large limps were torn from the tops of about a dozen pine trees, some falling onto a pickup truck.
A tornado touched down briefly on the north side of Governors Road and moved northwest for about a tenth of a mile. About a dozen small pine trees were broken off.
Video captured a waterspout that came ashore as a tornado near 21st Ave in Myrtle Beach.

The tornado, associated with a line of storms trailing Tropical Cyclone Florence, was shown live on air by a local television station as viewed from their skycam. It caused minor damage to the tops of pine trees, breaking out numerous small limbs and a few large ones before it crossed Highway 17 moving west. Additional minor tree damage occurred on the west side of Highway 17 before the fast moving tornado lifted.

A weak tornado touched down south of Lester Road between the Little Pee Dee River and Riverview Loop. It crossed Lester Road moving north, and broke large limbs out of several trees. A few small pine trees were also broken off and knocked across the road.
A sheriff observed a tornado that touched down on a nearby field off of Gaddys Mill Road.

A tornado touched down near SR 17-198 just south of Vicksburg Drive, and skipped north along the east side of West Country Club Road. Several large limbs were were broken out of tree tops, along with a few snapped small pine trees and hardwoods. Additional minor tree damage was observed on the east side of Oscar Drive to near the intersection with Harlees Bridge Road, where several limbs were broken from the tops of oak trees.

A tornado touched down south of SR 1134 and moved north, breaking limbs from a few tree tops before crossing an open field. A stand of half a dozen large oak trees on the north side of SR 1134 sustained significant damage, with numerous large limbs broken out. One large oak broke off near ground level. The tornado continued north across open field, then broke limbs out of the tops of trees before lifting.

A tornado broke large limbs out of the tops of trees on the east side of Blue Moon Drive. It moved north across open field, then broke additional limbs from trees before crossing Harlees Bridge Road. Several small pine trees were snapped along the north side of Harlees Bridge Road.
A tornado touched down in northern Horry County causing spotty damage to pine trees and minor roof damage.

A tornado associated with tropical cylcone Florence touched down during the early morning of September 17th, just southeast of Roseboro. This tornado continued on the ground for roughly 13 minutes mostly impacting trees, farm buildings, and eventually a car dealership within the city of Roseboro. The storm continued to weaken as it pushed northwest, crossing highway 24, and continuing to produce intermittent tree damage prior to lifting southwest of Salemburg. Property damages were estimated.

A short lived and weak tornado associated with Florence touched down in the pre-dawn hours just east of the Wayne Executive Jetport runway. The tornado was only on the ground for a short amount of time, but did cause some minor structural damage to a home and destroyed several outbuildings before lifting. Property damages were estimated.

A short lived and weak tornado associated with Tropical Depression
Florence touched down just south and southwest of the Wayne Executive 
Jetport. Damage consisted of several snapped and uprooted trees, and 
minor structural damage to a home.

A weak and short-lived tornado associated with Florence touched down southwest of Elm City, NC just after dawn on September 17th, 2018. The tornado remained on the ground for roughly 1.2 miles, producing intermittent damage to primarily hardwood trees and under brush. Uprooted and snapped trees fell onto several cars and structures along the tornado path, with damage ending gradually on the northwest end of town. Property damages were estimated.

The tornado touched down near Skipwith Road and Moores Road where numerous trees were downed. The storm then tracked northeast, while intermittently touching down causing widespread tree damage. The tornado made its last touchdown near Highway 47 about 6 miles east of Chase City where numerous trees were downed near the Salem Methodist Church. Structure damage to several houses and outbuildings were noted, however all structure damage was due to downed trees.
This was a weak tornado that uprooted a few trees and snapped some tree limbs.
The tornado briefly touched down on New Kent Road where numerous trees were snapped.
The tornado touched down on West Wood Avenue, then onto Confederate Avenue and Lamont Street where numerous trees and several power poles were snapped.

The tornado touched down in the City of Richmond on the north side of the James River between Byrd Park and the Powhite Parkway. The tornado continued across the Powhite Parkway into the Windsor Farms section of the City of Richmond. The tornado mainly snapped and uprooted trees along its path.
Public video of a tornado touchdown near Atlee High School. Tornado touched down briefly then lifted off the ground causing no damage.
The tornado touched down near Stratford Road, then moved north across Chippenham Parkway, and ending near Cherokee Road where numerous trees and several power poles were snapped.

A weak landspout tornado formed northwest of the CR 718/350 intersection north-northwest of Stratton. The tornado lasted for atleast two minutes, remaining stationary. No damage occurred due to the tornado remaining in an open field.

A NWS storm survey concluded that an EF0 tornado, with maximum winds of 70 mph, and a width of 70 yards, touched down in a field near Garden City. This tornado tracked 1.2 miles northeast through a farmstead and fairground, before dissipating in a corn field northeast of town. Most of the damage was associated with trees blown down, and a flattened corn fields.

A NWS storm survey, plus video from a drone, concluded that an EF0 tornado touched down north of Rapidan, and moved east for approximately a mile. Damage was confined to a field, and two homes. The main damage was to a home that had a tree fall on its roof.
High resolution satellite data and ground surveys confirmed a narrow track through corn east of Janesville. Maximum width was 20 yards with estimated wind damage of 70 mph.

A NWS storm survey, plus areal footage of drone and satellite data, concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked 5.5 miles from the intersection of I-35 and 130th Street West, northeast to the city of Dundas. This tornado started with damage to a billboard on I-35 with uprooted pine trees, then mainly damage to corn and soy bean fields, and it ended with several large trees uprooted in Dundas. The damage was consistent with EF0 damage with maximum wind speeds of 75 mph and a width of 75 yards.

A NWS storm survey, plus areal footage of drone and satellite data, concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked east of Kenyon, then northeast for 8.2 miles before lifting west of Zumbrota. This tornado tracked mainly through corn and soy bean fields, and occasionally damaged a few sheds and outbuildings. The damage was consistent with EF0 damage with maximum wind speeds of 75 mph and a width of 250 yards.

A NWS storm survey, plus drone and satellite footage, concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked 2.5 miles from east of Randolph, to the Goodhue County line, north of Highway 29. Most of the damage was associated with corn and soy bean fields flatten. Maximum width was 70 yards with estimated wind damage of 70 mph. 	This is the continued tornado track from the Dakota County tornado that moved an additional 0.7 miles east into Goodhue County. A storm survey concluded that EF0 damage occurred to a warehouse building in northern Goodhue County.

A NWS storm survey, plus areal footage of drone and satellite data, concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked 4.6 miles from south of Hampton, then east-northeast before it lifted 2 miles east of New Trier. This tornado tracked mainly through corn and soy bean fields, and occasionally damaging a few sheds and outbuildings. The damage was consistent with EF0 damage with maximum wind speeds of 75 mph and a width of 220 yards.

A NWS storm survey, plus areal footage of drone and satellite data, concluded that an EF0 tornado started north of Zumbrota, and tracked northeast for 5.4 miles until moving into Wabasha County, southwest of Bellechester. This tornado tracked mainly through corn and soy bean fields, and occasionally damaging a few sheds and outbuildings. The damage was consistent with EF0 damage with maximum wind speeds of 85 mph and a width of 150 yards. This the continuation of a tornado that began in Goodhue County. A NWS Storm Survey team found that the tornado moved briefly across the far northwest corner of Wabasha County north of Mazeppa before moving back into Goodhue County. Damage was limited to crops. This is the continuation of the Goodhue-Wabasha County tornado that tracked briefly into Wabasha County, before moving back into Goodhue County, and dissipated approximately 3/4 of a mile west of Bellechester. Areal footage of drone, satellite data and a storm survey, indicated EF0 damage in a corn field.

A NWS storm survey concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked eastward for 2.6 miles across the Mississippi River Valley, to the Wisconsin state line. The tornado tracked only one quarter of a mile north of the Treasure Island Resort and Casino. Damage was confined to uprooted trees and an outbuilding. The tornado continued into Pierce County Wisconsin. This is a continuation of a tornado that tracked from Goodhue County in Minnesota, then across the Mississippi River near Diamond Bluff. This tornado tracked for 0.6 miles in Pierce County before dissipating. EF0 damage was observed from trees and power lines based on a storm survey.
A NWS storm survey concluded that an EF0 tornado tracked from the Village of Ellsworth, northeast for 1.67 miles before dissipating. Damage was confined to large trees blown down or uprooted.

A small, brief EF-0 tornado touched down on the west side of Bradyville Road just north of Lassiter Road. Moving NNE, the tornado caused significant roof damage to two homes on the west side of the roadway. Further NNE, an old barn was destroyed where three men escaped injury, and another home built in the 1890s sustained minor roof damage with several trees blown down. Several eyewitness accounts and a video posted to Youtube showed this tornado skipped along its path and was only on the ground 1-2 minutes. This is the first tornado on record to occur in the month of September in Cannon County.

A NWS storm survey team determined a stronger EF0 tornado touched down northwest of Winfield Iowa. Damage to trees and corn was noted along its over a quarter mile path. The max width was estimated to be 20 yards and strongest winds were estimated to be 85 mph.

A NWS storm survey team determined a brief tornado touched down and lofted two empty grain bins and damaged some corn. Max winds are estimated near 80 mph. The maximum width was 20 yards and the path length was .05 miles.

An EF0 tornado began in Berlin Township in Monroe County just south of Sigler Road on North Dixie Highway. The tornado moved northeast about 2 miles before exiting Monroe County in South Rockwood. The tornado continue for another 2 miles before dissipating in Wayne County. The tornado remained at EF0 strength throughout the entire path. Damage in Monroe County included multiple limbs and large trees downed. This tornado began in Berlin Township in Monroe County about 2 miles south of South Rockwood. The tornado entered Wayne County in Rockwood and then continued for another 2 miles, before dissipating near the intersection of Meadow Lane and Ostreich Road near the border of Brownstown Charter Township and the city of Gibraltar. The tornado remained at EF0 strength throughout the entire path length. Damage included multiple limbs and large trees downed, along with missing shingles to a house near the end of the tornado path.

Eyewitness accounts and several videos confirm that a tornado initially touched down just west of the Moonlight Drive-In Theatre along US322 just west of Brookville. Sporadic minor to moderate tree damage was observed along a 4 mile track to the east, last observed along Kirkman Rd just north of the 82 mile marker of Interstate 80. The track is presumed to have crossed Interstate 80 roughly at the North Fork Creek bridge.

An EF-0 tornado was confirmed by a NWS Storm Survey to have occurred near Toby in Elk County, PA on October 2, 2018. Several trees were felled in a convergent pattern, although some of the terrain was inaccessible due to its rugged nature. The path length was less than a quarter of a mile, with an approximate maximum path width of 20 yards and a maximum wind speed estimated at 65-75 mph.

From eyewitness reports and visible damage, a brief tornado began near a hilltop along Brinker Road and continued northeastward toward Rt 819.
Several trees, both softwood and hardwood, in the area of Gold Leaf Lane were snapped and many others were uprooted. The tornado grew smaller rapidly as it crossed Rt 819 and leveled trees in the woods behind homes along Armbrust-Hecla Road before it weakened quickly. No additional damage points were found by the survey team after this point.
Tree damage was found along Stone Church Road, but appears to have been produced by strong wind outside of the tornadic circulation, perhaps associated with the rear-flank downdraft or a core collapse in the forward flank of the storm.
A small tornado touched down briefly along Aston Mountain Road and quickly lifted. Maximum winds were estimated at 80 mph. This tornado downed and snapped numerous trees in a concentrated small path.
A small tornado descended and tore the roof off of a barn. Maximum winds were estimated at 70 mph. The tornado then took down several trees at a residence near Elias Road before lifting.

The National Weather Service in Norton confirmed that a weak EF-0 tornado touched down in Mansfield, CT. This was based on a number of sources, including an eyewitness account, information from the Mansfield Emergency Management Agency Director, aerial drone footage provided by the media, and a weak tornado debris signature seen on Doppler radar.
Trees were downed, in a chaotic pattern, starting from just west of Storrs Road (Route 195) between Cemetery Road and Bassetts Bridge Road, continuing east-northeastward across Cemetery Road, and ending just to the east of the southernmost portion of Echo Road. Several shingles were blown off a roof on Storrs Road and were found 500 yards downwind. A person living on Centre Street, just west of Echo Lake observed a swirling mass of leaves and sticks passing to his southeast, some of which were hitting his house. The Mansfield Emergency Management Agency Director walked the path and found that downed trees north of Cemetery Road were facing the southwest while they were mainly facing northeast just to the south of Cemetery Road.

A National Weather Service Storm Survey of damage in the Hamlet of Ronkonkoma New York was conducted in conjunction with the Town of Islip. Based on the results of this survey and NWS Doppler Radar data the following information has been determined. The tornado originated just north of the western end of Seneca Street and ended about one-eighth of a mile east of the intersection of Mohican Avenue and Seneca Street. The damage was confined to between Iroquois and Ontario streets along Mohican Avenue. Numerous homes sustained damage to siding and gutters and outdoor furniture. Trees have visibly sheared tops, and at least two or three trees were downed on cars. This damage is consistent with maximum wind speeds of around 85 mph, making this an EF-0 tornado. The tornado had a maximum path width of around 200 yards and was on the ground continuously for around 400 yards.
Brief landspout tornado confirmed from the Callaghan Peak webcam.
A weak, fast-moving tornado caused only minor tree damage (DI 28, DOD 1-3) on the south side of the village of Mattoon.
A tornado touched down in a field and flattened corn as well as snapped tree branches about a 12 inches in diameter before crossing a road and dissipating. Peak winds with this tornado were 80 MPH.

This tornado was initially reported to Castro County Police by a motorist near Dimmitt. With time, this initially small tornado grew into a large cone as it moved north at about 30 mph. No known damage accompanied this tornado as it remained over farm land.
Storm chasers observed a brief tornado approximately 3 miles northeast of Saddle Mountain, or about 12 miles east-northeast of Cooperton. No damage was reported.

Numerous storm chasers and storm spotters observed a relatively weak tornado that formed just east of Interstate 35 west of Davis. The tornado moved northeast crossing State Highway 7 into Garvin County near NS328 Road. Other than some tree limb damage, no other damage was reported.

This tornado developed over the southwestern portion of the town of Fairfax, where the roofs of homes were damaged, and power poles and large tree limbs were snapped. The tornado moved northeast across town damaging the roofs of a number of businesses, damaging homes, snapping large tree limbs, and blowing down power poles. Numerous windows of businesses and homes were broken due to flying debris. The tornado moved east-northeast from Fairfax, crossing County Road 5701 where large tree limbs were snapped, then dissipated over open country. Based on this damage, maximum estimated wind in the tornado was 80 to 85 mph.
A video was taken of a brief and weak tornado that occurred between Jolly and Kay Roads.

A small brief tornado developed along a line of storms. It tracked northeast and damaged one known farmstead. Start and end points and time is estimated based on tornado damage signature dual-pol radar data and damage report. Estimated path of 3-4 miles.

A thunderstorm moved across Upton County and produced a tornado near McCamey. The tornado touched down four miles north of McCamey for a couple of seconds in an open field then lifted. It was classified as an EF-0.
A photo was taken by a resident of a fully condensed tornado near Highway FF and Road B. Powerlines and tree limbs were across the roadway at FF and 170th.

QLCS tornado developed along the leading edge of the convection in northeast rural Guthrie County. The tornado remained in cropland for its entire path producing plenty of crop damage along with topping trees in a few different groves. The path was initially narrow but broadened as it continued northeast. Only toward the end of the track did it narrow once more. Damage path was also visible on high resolution satellite imagery.

A brief tornado occurred north of Crawford near the intersection of Prairie Chapel Road and Tonk Creek. The tornado traveled north for a short time into a field. Damage was limited to a few tree limbs.

A small, weak tornado developed near NE 23rd Street and Kelley Avenue and moving northeast to an area just southeast of NE 36th Street and Prospect Avenue. This tornado produced damage to a power pole just south of NE 23rd Street and a snapped a few tree branches along the path. One tree snapped falling onto a carport and car along Prospect Avenue.

The tornado developed just north of Lindsey Street near the southwestern part of Lake Thunderbird between 84th Avenue SE and 108th Avenue SE, then moved northeast across the western part of Lake Thunderbird. The tornado moved off the lake south of Alameda Drive and 108th Avenue NE and continued northeast before dissipating just east of 120th Avenue SE and Rock Creek Road. Damage was confined to trees along the path.

Initial damage was observed near NE 122nd Street and Interstate 35 in northeastern Oklahoma City. The tornado moved generally northeast across east Edmond, crossing the northwestern portion of Arcadia Lake, then dissipating southeast of Danforth Road and Midwest Boulevard. Except for power pole and fencing damage at the beginning of the path, damage was limited to sporadic tree damage.

An outbuilding was damaged as a tornado developed just south of NE 23rd Street and Choctaw Road. The tornado then produced sporadic tree damage as it move northeast to near NE 63rd Street and Peebly Road.
A tornado touched down briefly on the south side of Prague. The tornado flipped a car over a truck into another truck in a parking lot in Prague.

A brief tornado formed from a low-topped supercell and traveled over mainly farmland, downing a few trees across secondary roadways. This tornado crossed into Caldwell County when it crossed Price Road. This is a continuation of a tornado that formed in northern Ray County and crossed Price Road into Caldwell County. The tornado did some minor tree damage along its path.

The tornado developed near the Centerville Municipal Airport with one of the hangars sustaining EF0 damage. The tornado proceeded through cropland up to the southwest outskirts of Centerville before dissipating.
Brief tornado reported by a storm chaser south of Rathbun. This tornado stayed in rural crop and grazing land with little to no damage.
A brief tornado was observed by a broadcast meteorologist. The tornado touched down in a field and lasted for less than 30 seconds. No damage was reported.
Tornado developed west of the hamlet of Ewart and moved due north. Tornado remained in rural agricultural land with little damage.
A brief tornado occurred and caused some very minor tree damage.
